# kuberntes workload managemet 

kubernetes pod is a compute fundamentals: 
- deployment  ::::: deployment based for application; You describe a desired state in a Deployment, and the Deployment Controller changes the actual state to the desired state at a controlled rate. You can define Deployments to create new ReplicaSets, 
   or to remove existing Deployments and adopt all their resources with new Deployments.
  - if yourapplication needs to be scaled up or down, you can simply change the number of replicas in the Deployment, and the Deployment Controller will take care of scaling the application up or down as needed.
  - if applciation manage state in this can we not use deployment because if we use deployment and if the pod is restarted then the state will be lost so in that case we can use statefulset because statefulset will maintain the state of the application even if the pod is restarted.
  
- statefulset  ::::: database mysql msql, cassandra, redis, elasticsearch, zookeeper, kafka, rabbitmq, etc. 
  - if your application needs to maintain state, you can use a StatefulSet, which provides guarantees about the ordering and uniqueness of pods. StatefulSets are designed for applications that require stable, unique network identifiers and persistent storage.
  - if your application needs to maintain state, you can use a StatefulSet, which provides guarantees about the ordering and uniqueness of pods. StatefulSets are designed for applications that require stable, unique network identifiers and persistent storage.

- daemonset :::: pod is running on all the nodes in the cluster. 
  - if you want to run a pod on all the nodes in the cluster, you can use a DaemonSet. DaemonSets are typically used for running system-level services, such as log collection or monitoring agents, on every node in the cluster.
  - logging storage networking monitoring security

- job ::::: one time task 
  - if you want to run a one-time task, you can use a Job. Jobs are used for running batch processes or other tasks that need to be completed once and then exit. Jobs can be configured to run a specified number of times, and they will automatically retry failed tasks until they succeed or reach the specified number of retries.

- cronjob ::::: scheduled task 
  - if you want to run a task on a schedule, you can use a CronJob. CronJobs are used for running tasks at specific times or intervals, similar to the cron utility in Unix-like operating systems. You can specify the schedule using a cron expression, and the CronJob will create Jobs according to that schedule.

- replica set :::: default manage pod no of replicas; default enable in deployment and statefulset 

- pod :::: single manage pod


# scaling - horizontal pod autoscaler :::: scale up or down the number of pods based on CPU utilization or other select metric
---
apiVersion: autoscaling/v2
kind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler
metadata:
  name: jenkins-server-hpa
  namespace: build 
spec:
  scaleTargetRef:
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: Deployment
    name: jenkins-server-deployment
  minReplicas: 1
  maxReplicas: 5
  metrics:
  - type: Resource
    resource:
      name: cpu
      target:
        type: Utilization
        averageUtilization: 50
    memory:
      name: memory
      target:
        type: Utilization
        averageUtilization: 50

# kucectl autoscale deployment jenkins-server-deployment --cpu-percent=50 --min=1 --max=5 -n build 

# scaling - vertical pod autoscaler :::: scale up or down the resources of the pod based on CPU utilization or other select metric
---
apiVersion: autoscaling.k8s.io/v1
kind: VerticalPodAutoscaler 
metadata:
  name: jenkins-server-vpa
  namespace: build
spec:
  targetRef:
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: Deployment
    name: jenkins-server-deployment
  updatePolicy:
    updateMode: "InPlaceOrRecreate"
  resourcePolicy:
    containerPolicies:  
    - containerName: jenkins
      minAllowed:
        cpu: 100m
        memory: 128Mi
      maxAllowed:
        cpu: 1
        memory: 1Gi
